Name: Aphrodite
Description: Goddess of beauty, love, desire, and pleasure. In Hesiod's Theogony (188–206), she was born from sea-foam and the severed genitals of Uranus; in Homer's Iliad (5.370–417), she is daughter of Zeus and Dione. She was married to Hephaestus, but bore him no children. She had many lovers, most notably Ares, to whom she bore Harmonia, Phobos, and Deimos. She was also a lover to Adonis and Anchises, to whom she bore Aeneas. She is usually depicted as a naked or semi-nude beautiful woman. Her symbols include the magical girdle, myrtle, roses, and the scallop shell. Her sacred animals include doves and sparrows. Her Roman counterpart is Venus.[1]

Name: Apollo
Description: God of music, arts, knowledge, healing, plague, prophecy, poetry, manly beauty, and archery. He is the son of Zeus and Leto, and the twin brother of Artemis. Both Apollo and Artemis use a bow and arrow. Apollo is depicted as young, beardless, handsome and athletic. In myth, he can be cruel and destructive, and his love affairs are rarely happy. He is often accompanied by the Muses. His most famous temple is in Delphi, where he established his oracular shrine. His signs and symbols include the laurel wreath, bow and arrow, and lyre. His sacred animals include roe deer, swans, and pythons. Some late Roman and Greek poetry and mythography identifies him as a sun-god, equivalent to Roman Sol and Greek Helios.[2]

Name: Ares
Description: God of music, arts, knowledge, healing, plague, prophecy, poetry, manly beauty, and archery. He is the son of Zeus and Leto, and the twin brother of Artemis. Both Apollo and Artemis use a bow and arrow. Apollo is depicted as young, beardless, handsome and athletic. In myth, he can be cruel and destructive, and his love affairs are rarely happy. He is often accompanied by the Muses. His most famous temple is in Delphi, where he established his oracular shrine. His signs and symbols include the laurel wreath, bow and arrow, and lyre. His sacred animals include roe deer, swans, and pythons. Some late Roman and Greek poetry and mythography identifies him as a sun-god, equivalent to Roman Sol and Greek Helios.[2]

Name: Artemis
Description: Virgin goddess of the hunt, wilderness, animals, the Moon and young girls. Both she and Apollo are archery gods. She is the daughter of Zeus and Leto, and twin sister of Apollo. In art she is often depicted as a young woman dressed in a short knee-length chiton and equipped with a silver hunting bow and a quiver of arrows. Her attributes include hunting knives and spears, animal pelts, deer and other wild animals. Her sacred animal is a deer. Her Roman counterpart is Diana.[4]

Name: Athena
Description: Goddess of reason, wisdom, intelligence, skill, peace, warfare, battle strategy, and handicrafts. According to most traditions, she was born from Zeus's forehead, fully formed and armored. She is depicted as being crowned with a crested helm, armed with shield and spear, and wearing the aegis over a long dress. Poets describe her as "grey-eyed" or having especially bright, keen eyes. She is a special patron of heroes such as Odysseus. She is the patron of the city Athens (from which she takes her name) and is attributed to various inventions in arts and literature. Her symbol is the olive tree. She is commonly shown as being accompanied by her sacred animal, the owl. Her Roman counterpart is Minerva.[5]

Name: Demeter
Description: Goddess of grain, agriculture, harvest, growth, and nourishment. Demeter, whose Roman counterpart is Ceres, is a daughter of Cronus and Rhea, and was swallowed and then regurgitated by her father. She is a sister of Zeus, by whom she bore Persephone, who is also known as Kore, i.e. "the girl." One of the central myths associated with Demeter involves Hades' abduction of Persephone and Demeter's lengthy search for her. Demeter is one of the main deities of the Eleusinian Mysteries, in which the rites seemed to center around Demeter's search for and reunion with her daughter, which symbolized both the rebirth of crops in spring and the rebirth of the initiates after death. She is depicted as a mature woman, often crowned and holding sheafs of wheat and a torch.[6] Her symbols are the cornucopia, wheat-ears, the winged serpent, and the lotus staff. Her sacred animals include pigs and snakes.

Name: Dionysus
Description: God of wine, fruitfulness, parties, festivals, madness, chaos, drunkenness, vegetation, ecstasy, and the theater. He is the twice-born son of Zeus and Semele, in that Zeus snatched him from his mother's womb and stitched Dionysus into his own thigh and carried him until he was ready to be born. In art he is depicted as either an older bearded god (particularly before 430 BC) or an effeminate, long-haired youth (particularly after 430 BC). His attributes include the thyrsus, a drinking cup, the grape vine, and a crown of ivy. He is often in the company of his thiasos, a group of attendants including satyrs, maenads, and his old tutor Silenus. The consort of Dionysus was Ariadne. It was once held that Dionysius was a later addition to the Greek pantheon, but the discovery of Linear B tablets confirm his status as a deity from an early period. Bacchus was another name for him in Greek, and came into common usage among the Romans.[7] His sacred animals include dolphins, serpents, tigers, and donkeys.

Name: Hades
Description: King of the underworld and the dead. He is also a god of wealth. His consort is Persephone. His attributes are the drinking horn or cornucopia, key, sceptre, and the three-headed dog Cerberus. His sacred animals include the screech owl. He was one of three sons of Cronus and Rhea, and thus sovereign over one of the three realms of the universe, the underworld. As a chthonic god, however, his place among the Olympians is ambiguous. In the mystery religions and Athenian literature, Plouton ("the Rich one") was his preferred name, because of the idea that all riches came from the earth. The term Hades was used in this literature to refer to the underworld itself. The Romans translated Plouton as Dis Pater ("the Rich Father") or Pluto.[8]

Name: Hephaestus
Description: God of fire, metalworking, and crafts. Either the son of Zeus and Hera or Hera alone, he is the smith of the gods and the husband of the adulterous Aphrodite. He was usually depicted as a bearded, crippled man with hammer, tongs, and anvil, and sometimes riding a donkey. His sacred animals include the donkey, the guard dog, and the crane. Among his creations was the armor of Achilles. Hephaestus used the fire of the forge as a creative force, but his Roman counterpart Vulcan was feared for his destructive potential and associated with the volcanic power of the earth.

Name: Hera
Description: Queen of the gods, and goddess of women, marriage, childbirth, heirs, kings, and empires. She is the goddess of the sky, the wife and sister of Zeus, and the daughter of Cronus and Rhea. She was usually depicted as a regal woman in the prime of her life, wearing a diadem and veil and holding a lotus-tipped staff. Although she is the goddess of marriage, Zeus's many infidelities drive her to jealousy and vengefulness. Her sacred animals include the heifer, the peacock, and the cuckoo. Her Roman counterpart is Juno.

Name: Hermes
Description: God of boundaries, travel, trade, communication, language, writing, cunning and thieves. Hermes was also responsible for protecting livestock and presided over the spheres associated with fertility, music, luck, and deception.[9] The son of Zeus and Maia, Hermes is the messenger of the gods, and a psychopomp who leads the souls of the dead into the afterlife. He was depicted either as a handsome and athletic beardless youth, or as an older bearded man. His attributes include the herald's wand or caduceus, winged sandals, and a traveler's cap. His sacred animals include the tortoise. His Roman counterpart is Mercury.

Name: Hestia
Description: Virgin goddess of the hearth, home, domesticity and chastity. She is a daughter of Rhea and Cronus, and a sister of Zeus. Not often identifiable in Greek art, she appeared as a modestly veiled woman. Her symbols are the hearth and kettle. She plays little role in Greek myths, and although she is omitted in some lists of the twelve Olympians in favour of Dionysus, no ancient tale tells of her abdicating or giving her seat to Dionysus.[10] Her Roman counterpart Vesta, however, was a major deity of the Roman state.

Name: Poseidon
Description: God of the sea, rivers, floods, droughts, and earthquakes. He is a son of Cronus and Rhea, and the brother of Zeus and Hades. He rules one of the three realms of the universe, as king of the sea and the waters. In art he is depicted as a mature man of sturdy build, often with a luxuriant beard, and holding a trident. His sacred animals include the horse and the dolphin. His wedding with Amphitrite is often presented as a triumphal procession. In some stories he rapes Medusa, leading to her transformation into a hideous Gorgon and also to the birth of their two children, Pegasus and Chrysaor. His Roman counterpart is Neptune.

Name: Zeus
Description: King of the gods, ruler of Mount Olympus, and god of the sky, weather, thunder, lightning, law, order, and justice. He is the youngest son of Cronus and Rhea. He overthrew Cronus and gained the sovereignty of heaven for himself. In art he is depicted as a regal, mature man with a sturdy figure and dark beard. His usual attributes are the royal scepter and the lightning bolt. His sacred animals include the eagle and the bull. His Roman counterpart is Jupiter, also known as Jove.

Name: Alcis
Description: pair of young brothers worshipped by the Naharvali, an ancient Germanic tribe.

Name: Baldr
Description: son of the god Odin and the goddess Frigg, and has numerous brothers, such as Thor and Váli.

Name: Bragi
Description: is the skaldic god of poetry in Norse mythology.

Name: Dellingr
Description: possibly "the dayspring"[1] or "shining one"

Name: Forseti
Description: the god of justice and reconciliation

Name: Freyr
Description: "the most renowned of the æsir", and was venerated for good harvest and peace.

Name: Heimdall
Description: "the head is called his sword," and he is "the whitest of the gods."

Name: Hermóðr
Description: often considered the messenger of the gods.

Name: Höðr
Description: The blind son of Odin and Frigg

Name: Hœnir
Description: one of the three gods (along with Odin and Lóðurr) that created the first humans.

Name: Lóðurr
Description: he is assigned a role in animating the first humans

Name: Loki
Description: a shape shifter

Name: Móði and Magni
Description: names translate to "Wrath" and "Mighty," respectively.

Name: Máni
Description: Moon

Name: Mímir
Description: "Rememberer"

Name: Meili
Description: "the lovely one"

Name: Njörðr
Description: associated with the sea, seafaring, wind, fishing, wealth, and crop fertility.

Name: Odin
Description: Frenzy

Name: Óðr
Description: "Divine Madness, frantic, furious, vehement, eager"

Name: Seaxnēat
Description: the national god of the Saxons.

Name: Thor
Description: meaning 'Thunder'

Name: Tuisto
Description: the legendary divine ancestor of the Germanic peoples

Name: Týr
Description: a valorous and powerful member of the Æsir and patron of warriors and mythological heroes

Name: Ullr
Description: a god associated with archery.

Name: Váli
Description: He is prophesied to survive Ragnarök.

Name: Víðarr
Description: a god among the Æsir associated with vengeance.

Name: Vili and Vé
Description: brothers of the god Odin

Name: Baduhenna
Description: Badu-, may be cognate to Proto-Germanic *badwa- meaning "battle." The second portion of the name -henna may be related to -henae, which appears commonly in the names of matrons.

Name: Hjúki and Bil
Description: Hjúki (Old Norse: [ˈhiu̯ːke], possibly meaning "the one returning to health"[1]) and Bil (O.N.: [ˈbil], literally "instant"

Name: Beyla
Description: her name has been proposed as related to "cow," "bean," or "bee."

Name: Dís
Description: "lady"

Name: Eir
Description: a goddess or valkyrie associated with medical skill.

Name: Ēostre
Description: "East"

Name: Freyja
Description: goddess associated with love, beauty, fertility, sex, war, gold, and seiðr (magic for seeing and influencing the future)

Name: Frigg
Description: Derived from an Indo-European root meaning "Love"

Name: Fulla
Description: Possibly "bountiful"

Name: Gefjon
Description: a goddess associated with ploughing

Name: Gersemi
Description: means 'treasure'

Name: Gerðr
Description: "fenced-in"

Name: Gná and Hófvarpnir
Description: Gná (Old Norse: [ˈɡnɒː]) is a goddess who runs errands in other worlds for the goddess Frigg and rides the flying, sea-treading horse Hófvarpnir (O.N.: [ˈhoːvˌwɑrpnez̠], "he who throws his hoofs about",[1] "hoof-thrower"[2] or "hoof kicker"[3])

Name: Gullveig
Description: female figure in Norse mythology associated with the legendary conflict between the Æsir and Vanir.

Name: Hariasa
Description: Possibly related to the valkyrie name Herja or meaning "goddess with lots of hair"

Name: Hlín
Description: Possibly related to the Old Norse term hleinir, itself possibly meaning "protects"

Name: Hludana
Description: "The famous"

Name: Hnoss
Description: "treasure"

Name: Rheda
Description: possibly meaning "the famous" or "the victorious"

Name: Idis (Germanic)
Description: meaning 'well-respected and dignified woman.'

Name: Ilmr
Description: Potentially related to Old Norse ilmr, a masculine noun meaning "pleasant scent"

Name: Iðunn
Description: goddess associated with apples and youth.

Name: Þorgerðr Hölgabrúðr and Irpa
Description: Possibly relating to "dark brown"

Name: Lofn
Description: possibly "comforter,"[1] "the comforter, the mild,"[2] or "loving"[3]

Name: Nanna (Norse deity)
Description: a goddess associated with the god Baldr.

Name: Nehalennia
Description: a goddess of unclear origin, perhaps Germanic or Celtic.

Name: Nerthus
Description: a goddess associated with fertility.

Name: Njörun
Description: a goddess attested in the Prose Edda

Name: Norns
Description: esponsible for shaping the course of human destinies.[1]

Name: Rán
Description: a goddess and a personification of the sea.

Name: Rindr
Description: alternatively described as a giantess or a human princess from the east.

Name: Sága and Sökkvabekkr
Description: Sága (Old Norse: [sɑːɣɑ], possibly meaning "seeress"[1]) is a goddess associated with the location Sökkvabekkr (Old Norse: [ˈsøkːwɑˌbekːz̠]; "sunken bank", "sunken bench", or "treasure bank"[2])

Name: Sandraudiga
Description: "She who dyes the sand red."

Name: Sif
Description: is a golden-haired goddess associated with earth.

Name: Sigyn
Description: "(female) friend of victory"

Name: Sinthgunt
Description: referred to as the sister of the personified sun, Sunna

Name: Sjöfn
Description: a goddess associated with love.

Name: Skaði
Description: a jötunn and goddess associated with bowhunting, skiing, winter, and mountains.

Name: Snotra
Description: a goddess associated with wisdom.

Name: Sól
Description: the Sun personified in Germanic mythology

Name: Syn
Description: a goddess associated with defensive refusal.

Name: Tamfana
Description: fana is Latin for "temples," it has been suggested that it was a temple to a god Tan, shortened from the German word for a pine tree, Tanne, or that the first element meant "collective."

Name: Þrúðr
Description: "Power"

Name: Vár
Description: a goddess associated with oaths and agreements.

Name: Vör
Description: a goddess associated with wisdom.

Name: Zisa
Description: Possibly related to *Tiwaz

Name: Abundantia
Description: divine personification of abundance and prosperity.

Name: Acca Larentia
Description: a diva of complex meaning and origin in whose honor the Larentalia was held.

Name: Acis
Description: god of the Acis River in Sicily.

Name: Aerecura
Description: goddess possibly of Celtic origin, associated with the underworld and identified with Proserpina.

Name: Aequitas
Description: divine personification of fairness.

Name: Aesculapius
Description: the Roman equivalent of Asclepius, god of health and medicine.

Name: Aeternitas
Description: goddess and personification of eternity.

Name: Aion
Description: (Latin spelling Aeon), Hellenistic god of cyclical or unbounded time, related to the concepts of aevum or saeculum

Name: Aius Locutius
Description: divine voice that warned the Romans of the imminent Gallic invasion.

Name: Alernus
Description: an archaic god whose sacred grove (lucus) was near the Tiber river. He is named definitively only by Ovid.[29] The grove was the birthplace of the nymph Cranea, and despite the obscurity of the god, the state priests still carried out sacred rites (sacra) there in the time of Augustus.[30] Alernus may have been a chthonic god, if a black ox was the correct sacrificial offering to him, since dark victims were offered to underworld gods.[31] Dumézil wanted to make him a god of beans.[32]

Name: Angerona
Description: goddess who relieved people from pain and sorrow.

Name: Angitia
Description: goddess associated with snakes and Medea.

Name: Anna Perenna
Description: early goddess of the "circle of the year", her festival was celebrated March 15.

Name: Annona
Description: the divine personification of the grain supply to the city of Rome.

Name: Antevorta
Description: goddess of the future and one of the Camenae; also called Porrima.

Name: Apollo
Description: god of poetry, music, and oracles, and one of the Dii Consentes.

Name: Arimanius
Description: an obscure Mithraic god.

Name: Aura
Description: often plural Aurae, "the Breezes".

Name: Aurora
Description: goddess of the dawn.

Name: Averruncus
Description: a god propitiated to avert calamity.

Name: Bacchus
Description: god of wine, sensual pleasures, and truth, originally a cult title for the Greek Dionysus and identified with the Roman Liber.

Name: Bellona
Description: war goddess

Name: Bona Dea
Description: the "women's goddess"[33] with functions pertaining to fertility, healing, and chastity.

Name: Bonus Eventus
Description: divine personification of "Good Outcome".

Name: Bubona
Description: goddess of cattle.

Name: Caca
Description: an archaic fire goddess and "proto-Vesta";[34] the sister of Cacus.

Name: Cacus
Description: originally an ancient god of fire, later regarded as a giant.

Name: Caelus
Description: god of the sky before Jupiter.

Name: Camenae
Description: goddesses with various attributes including fresh water, prophecy, and childbirth. There were four of them: Carmenta, Egeria, Antevorta, and Postvorta.

Name: Cardea
Description: goddess of the hinge (cardo), identified by Ovid with Carna (below)

Name: Carmenta
Description: goddess of childbirth and prophecy, and assigned a flamen minor. The leader of the Camenae.

Name: Carmentes
Description: two goddesses of childbirth: Antevorta and Postvorta or Porrima, future and past.

Name: Carna
Description: goddess who preserved the health of the heart and other internal organs.

Name: Ceres
Description: goddess of the harvest and mother of Proserpina, and one of the Dii Consentes. The Roman equivalent of Demeter [Greek goddess].

Name: Clementia
Description: goddess of forgiveness and mercy.

Name: Cloacina
Description: goddess who presided over the system of sewers in Rome; identified with Venus.

Name: Concordia
Description: goddess of agreement, understanding, and marital harmony.

Name: Consus
Description: chthonic god protecting grain storage.

Name: Cupid
Description: Roman god of love. The son of Venus, and equivalent to Greek Eros.

Name: Cura
Description: personification of care and concern who according to a single source[35] created humans from clay.

Name: Cybele
Description: an imported tutelary goddess often identified with Magna Mater

Name: Dea Dia
Description: goddess of growth.

Name: Dea Tacita
Description: ("The Silent Goddess"), a goddess of the dead; later equated with the earth goddess Larenta.

Name: Decima
Description: minor goddess and one of the Parcae (Roman equivalent of the Moirai). The measurer of the thread of life, her Greek equivalent was Lachesis.

Name: Devera or Deverra
Description: goddess who ruled over the brooms used to purify temples in preparation for various worship services, sacrifices and celebrations; she protected midwives and women in labor.

Name: Diana
Description: goddess of the hunt, the moon, virginity, and childbirth, twin sister of Apollo and one of the Dii Consentes.

Name: Diana Nemorensis
Description: local version of Diana. The Roman equivalent of Artemis [Greek goddess]

Name: Discordia
Description: personification of discord and strife. The Roman equivalent of Eris [Greek goddess]

Name: Dius Fidius
Description: god of oaths, associated with Jupiter.

Name: Di inferi
Description: deities associated with death and the underworld.

Name: Disciplina
Description: personification of discipline.

Name: Dis Pater
Description: god of wealth and the underworld; perhaps a translation of Greek Plouton (Pluto).

Name: Egeria
Description: water nymph or goddess, later considered one of the Camenae.

Name: Empanda
Description: a goddess whose temple never closed to those in need.

Name: Epona
Description: Gallo-Roman goddess of horses and horsemanship, usually assumed to be of Celtic origin.

Name: Falacer
Description: obscure god. He was assigned a minor flamen.

Name: Fama
Description: goddess of fame and rumor

Name: Fascinus
Description: phallic god who protected from invidia (envy) and the evil eye.

Name: Fauna
Description: goddess of prophecy, but perhaps a title of other goddesses such as Maia.

Name: Faunus
Description: god of flocks.

Name: Faustitas
Description: goddess who protected herd and livestock.

Name: Februus
Description: god of Etruscan origin for whom the month of February was named; concerned with purification

Name: Febris
Description: "Fever," goddess with the power to cause or prevent fevers and malaria.

Name: Fecunditas
Description: personification of fertility.

Name: Felicitas
Description: personification of good luck and success.

Name: Ferentina
Description: patron goddess of the city Ferentinum, Latium, protector of the Latin commonwealth.

Name: Feronia
Description: goddess concerned with wilderness, plebeians, freedmen, and liberty in a general sense.

Name: Fides
Description: personification of loyalty.

Name: Flora
Description: goddess of flowers, was assigned a flamen minor.

Name: Fornax
Description: goddess probably conceived of to explain the Fornacalia, "Oven Festival."

Name: Fontus
Description: god of wells and springs.

Name: Fortuna
Description: goddess of fortune.

Name: Fufluns
Description: god of wine, natural growth and health. He was adopted from Etruscan religion.

Name: Fulgora
Description: personification of lightning.

Name: Furrina
Description: goddess whose functions are mostly unknown, but in archaic times important enough to be assigned a flamen.

Name: Genius
Description: the tutelary spirit or divinity of each individual

Name: Gratiae
Description: Roman term for the Charites or Graces.

Name: Hercules
Description: god of strength, whose worship was derived from the Greek hero Heracles but took on a distinctly Roman character.

Name: Hermaphroditus
Description: an androgynous Greek god whose mythology was imported into Latin literature.

Name: Honos
Description: a divine personification of honor.

Name: Hora
Description: the wife of Quirinus

Name: Indiges
Description: the deified Aeneas.

Name: Intercidona
Description: minor goddess of childbirth; invoked to keep evil spirits away from the child; symbolised by a cleaver.

Name: Inuus
Description: god of fertility and sexual intercourse, protector of livestock.

Name: Invidia
Description: goddess of envy and wrongdoing.

Name: Janus
Description: double-faced or two-headed god of beginnings and endings and of doors.

Name: Juno
Description: Queen of the gods, goddess of matrimony, and one of the Dii Consentes. Equivalent to Greek Hera.

Name: Jupiter
Description: King of the gods, god of storms, lightning, sky, and one of the Dii Consentes; was assigned a flamen maior. Equivalent to Greek Zeus.

Name: Justitia
Description: goddess of justice.

Name: Juturna
Description: goddess of fountains, wells, and springs.

Name: Juventas
Description: goddess of youth.

Name: Lares
Description: household gods.

Name: Latona
Description: goddess of light.

Name: Laverna
Description: patroness of thieves, con men and charlatans.

Name: Lemures
Description: the malevolent dead.

Name: Levana
Description: goddess of the rite through which fathers accepted newborn babies as their own.

Name: Letum
Description: personification of death.

Name: Liber
Description: a god of male fertility, viniculture and freedom, assimilated to Roman Bacchus and Greek Dionysus.

Name: Libera
Description: Liber's female equivalent, assimilated to Roman Proserpina and Greek Persephone.

Name: Liberalitas
Description: goddess or personification of generosity.

Name: Libertas
Description: goddess or personification of freedom.

Name: Libitina
Description: goddess of death, corpses and funerals.

Name: Lua
Description: goddess to whom soldiers sacrificed captured weapons, probably a consort of Saturn.

Name: Lucifer
Description: god of the morning star

Name: Lucina
Description: goddess of childbirth, but often as an aspect of Juno.

Name: Luna
Description: goddess of the moon.

Name: Lupercus
Description: god of shepherds and wolves; as the god of the Lupercalia, his identity is obscure, but he is sometimes identified with the Greek god Pan.

Name: Lympha
Description: often plural lymphae, a water deity assimilated to the Greek nymphs.

Name: Mana Genita
Description: goddess of infant mortality

Name: Manes
Description: the souls of the dead who came to be seen as household deities.

Name: Mania
Description: the consort of the Etruscan underworld god Mantus, and perhaps to be identified with the tenebrous Mater Larum; not to be confused with the Greek Maniae.

Name: Mantus
Description: an Etruscan god of the dead and ruler of the underworld.

Name: Mars
Description: god of war and father of Romulus, the founder of Rome; one of the Archaic Triad assigned a flamen maior; lover of Venus; one of the Dii Consentes.Greek equivalent-Ares.

Name: Mater Matuta
Description: goddess of dawn and childbirth, patroness of mariners.

Name: Meditrina
Description: goddess of healing, introduced to account for the festival of Meditrinalia.

Name: Mefitis
Description: goddess and personification of poisonous gases and volcanic vapours.

Name: Mellona
Description: goddess of bees and bee-keeping.

Name: Mena
Description: goddess of fertility and menstruation.

Name: Mercury
Description: messenger of the gods and bearer of souls to the underworld, and one of the Dii Consentes. Roman counterpart of the Greek god Hermes.

Name: Minerva
Description: goddess of wisdom, war, the arts, industries and trades, and one of the Dii Consentes. Roman equivalent of the Greek goddess Athena.

Name: Mithras
Description: god worshipped in the Roman empire; popular with soldiers.

Name: Molae
Description: daughters of Mars, probably goddesses of grinding of the grain.

Name: Moneta
Description: minor goddess of memory, equivalent to the Greek Mnemosyne. Also used as an epithet of Juno.

Name: Mors
Description: personification of death and equivalent of the Greek Thanatos.

Name: Morta
Description: minor goddess of death and one of the Parcae (Roman equivalent of the Moirai). The cutter of the thread of life, her Greek equivalent was Atropos.

Name: Murcia
Description: a little-known goddess who was associated with the myrtle, and in other sources was called a goddess of sloth and laziness (both interpretations arising from false etymologies of her name). Later equated with Venus in the form of Venus Murcia.

Name: Mutunus Tutunus
Description: a phallic god.

Name: Naenia
Description: goddess of funerary lament.

Name: Nascio
Description: personification of the act of birth.

Name: Necessitas
Description: goddess of destiny, the Roman equivalent of Ananke.

Name: Nemesis
Description: goddess of revenge (Greek), adopted as an Imperial deity of retribution.

Name: Neptune
Description: god of the sea, earthquakes, and horses, and one of the Dii Consentes. Greek equivalent is Poseidon.

Name: Nerio
Description: ancient war goddess and the personification of valor. The consort of Mars.

Name: Neverita
Description: presumed a goddess, and associated with Consus and Neptune in the Etrusco-Roman zodiac of Martianus Capella but otherwise unknown.[

Name: Nixi
Description: also di nixi, dii nixi, or Nixae, goddesses of childbirth.

Name: Nona
Description: minor goddess, one of the Parcae (Roman equivalent of the Moirai). The spinner of the thread of life, her Greek equivalent was Clotho.

Name: Nortia
Description: a Roman-adopted Etruscan goddess of fate, destiny, and chance from the city of Volsinii, where a nail was driven into a wall of her temple as part a new-year ceremony.

Name: Nox
Description: goddess of night, derived from the Greek Nyx.

Name: Ops
Description: goddess of resources or plenty.

Name: Orcus
Description: a god of the underworld and punisher of broken oaths.

Name: Palatua
Description: obscure goddess who guarded the Palatine Hill. She was assigned a flamen minor.

Name: Pales
Description: deity of shepherds, flocks and livestock.

Name: Parcae
Description: the three fates.

Name: Pax
Description: goddess of peace; equivalent of Greek Eirene.

Name: Penates
Description: household gods.

Name: Picumnus
Description: minor god of fertility, agriculture, matrimony, infants and children.

Name: Picus
Description: Italic woodpecker god with oracular powers.

Name: Pietas
Description: goddess of duty; personification of the Roman virtue pietas.

Name: Pilumnus
Description: minor guardian god, concerned with the protection of infants at birth.

Name: Pluto
Description: Greek Plouton, a name for the ruler of the dead popularized through the mystery religions and Greek philosophy, sometimes used in Latin literature and identified with Dis pater or Orcus.

Name: Poena
Description: goddess of punishment.

Name: Pomona
Description: goddess of fruit trees, gardens and orchards; assigned a flamen minor.

Name: Porrima
Description: goddess of the future. Also called Antevorta. One of the Carmentes and the Camenae.

Name: Portunus
Description: god of keys, doors, and livestock, he was assigned a flamen minor.

Name: Postverta or Prorsa Postverta
Description: goddess of childbirth and the past, one of the two Carmentes (other being Porrima).

Name: Priapus
Description: imported phallic guardian of guardians.

Name: Proserpina
Description: Queen of the Dead and a grain-goddess, the Roman equivalent of the Greek Persephone.

Name: Providentia
Description: goddess of forethought.

Name: Pudicitia
Description: goddess and personification of chastity, one of the Roman virtues. Her Greek equivalent was Aidôs.

Name: Querquetulanae
Description: nymphs of the oak.

Name: Quirinus
Description: Sabine god identified with Mars; Romulus, the founder of Rome, was deified as Quirinus after his death. Quirinus was a war god and a god of the Roman people and state, and was assigned a flamen maior; he was one of the Archaic Triad gods.

Name: Quiritis
Description: goddess of motherhood. Originally Sabine or pre-Roman, she was later equated with Juno.

Name: Robigo or Robigus
Description: a god or goddess who personified grain disease and protected crops.

Name: Roma
Description: personification of the Roman state.

Name: Rumina
Description: goddess who protected breastfeeding mothers.

Name: Salacia
Description: goddess of seawater, wife of Neptune.

Name: Salus
Description: goddess of the public welfare of the Roman people; came to be equated with the Greek Hygieia.

Name: Sancus
Description: god of loyalty, honesty, and oaths.

Name: Saturn
Description: a titan, god of harvest and agriculture, the father of Jupiter, Neptune, Juno, and Pluto.

Name: Securitas
Description: goddess of security, especially the security of the Roman empire.

Name: Silvanus
Description: god of woodlands and forests.

Name: Sol Invictus
Description: sun god.

Name: Somnus
Description: god of sleep; equates with the Greek Hypnos.

Name: Soranus
Description: a god later subsumed by Apollo in the form Apollo Soranus.

Name: Sors
Description: god of luck.

Name: Spes
Description: goddess of hope.

Name: Stata Mater
Description: goddess who protected against fires. Sometimes equated with Vesta.

Name: Sterquilinus
Description: god of fertilizer. Also known as Stercutus, Sterculius, Straculius, Struculius.

Name: Suadela
Description: goddess of persuasion, her Greek equivalent was Peitho.

Name: Summanus
Description: god of nocturnal thunder.

Name: Sulis Minerva
Description: a conflation of the Celtic goddess Sul and Minerva

Name: Talasius
Description: a god of marriage

Name: Tellumo or Tellurus
Description: male counterpart of Tellus.

Name: Tempestas
Description: a goddess of storms or sudden weather, usually plural as the Tempestates

Name: Terra Mater or Tellus
Description: goddess of the earth and land. The Greek equivalent is Gaea, mother of titans, consort of Caelus (Uranus).

Name: Terminus
Description: the rustic god of boundaries.

Name: Tiberinus
Description: river god; deity of the Tiber river.

Name: Tibertus
Description: god of the river Anio, a tributary of the Tiber.

Name: Tranquillitas
Description: goddess of peace and tranquility.

Name: Trivia
Description: goddess of crossroads and magic, equated with Hecate.

Name: Vacuna
Description: ancient Sabine goddess of rest after harvest who protected the farmers' sheep; later identified with Nike and worshipped as a war goddess.

Name: Vagitanus, or Vaticanus
Description: opens the newborn's mouth for its first cry.

Name: Vediovus or Veiovis
Description: obscure god, a sort of anti-Jupiter, as the meaning of his name suggests. May be a god of the underworld.

Name: Venilia or Venelia
Description: sea goddess, wife of Neptune or Faunus.

Name: Venti
Description: the winds, equivalent to the Greek Anemoi: North wind Aquilo(n) or Septentrio (Greek Boreas); South wind Auster (Greek Notus); East wind Vulturnus (Eurus); West wind Favonius (Zephyrus); Northwest wind Caurus or Corus (see minor winds).

Name: Venus
Description: goddess of love, beauty, sexuality, and gardens; mother of the founding hero Aeneas; one of the Dii Consentes.

Name: Veritas
Description: goddess and personification of the Roman virtue of veritas or truth.

Name: Verminus
Description: god of cattle worms.

Name: Vertumnus, Vortumnus or Vertimnus
Description: god of the seasons, and of gardens and fruit trees.

Name: Vesta
Description: goddess of the hearth, the Roman state, and the sacred fire; one of the Dii Consentes.

Name: Vica Pota
Description: goddess of victory and competitions.

Name: Victoria
Description: goddess of victory.

Name: Viduus
Description: god who separated the soul and body after death.

Name: Virbius
Description: a forest god, the reborn Hippolytus.

Name: Virtus
Description: god or goddess of military strength, personification of the Roman virtue of virtus.

Name: Volturnus
Description: god of water, was assigned a flamen minor. Not to be confused with Vulturnus.

Name: Voluptas
Description: goddess of pleasure.

Name: Vulcan
Description: god of the forge, fire, and blacksmiths, husband to Venus, and one of the Dii Consentes, was assigned a flamen minor.
